<section id="nav">
    <h1>Navigating RStudio</h1>
    <p>
        To actually write R code, you will need to use RStudio. When you open the
        application, you will see something like this:
    </p>
    <img class="image-full-page" src="../img/00-img/rstudio.png" 
    style="display:block;margin:auto"/>
    <p>
        You'll need to create a new file to begin writing your code. You can do that 
        with <a href="./00-03-the-file-ecosystem.html">either a <code>.R</code> or <code>.Rmd

        </code> file</a> like so:
    </p>
    <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto" 
    src="../img/00-img/new-file.png">
    <p>
        You'll now see there are four distinctive areas of the RStudio window. 
        You can control where each of these panels exists, but this is the default layout:
    </p>
    <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto" 
    src="../img/00-img/four-panels.png">

    <section id="nav--scripts">
        <h3>
            Scripts Panel
        </h3>
        <p>
            The top left panel is where you'll spend most of your time. This is where 
            your script files (i.e. <code>.R</code> or <code>.Rmd</code> files) 
            will be displayed, and where you'll write code.
        </p>
        <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto"
        src="../img/00-img/scripts.png">
        <p>
            You can have multiple scripts/files open at once and toggle between them.
        </p>        
    </section>
    <section id="nav--console">
        <h3>Console</h3>
        <p>
            The console is your direct connection to R. You can type out code onto the 
            line with the carrot <code>></code> and press enter, to execute that line 
            of code. <b>However, note that here unlike code written in a script, that 
                code will not be saved for you to run again.</b>
        </p>
        <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto"
        src="../img/00-img/console.png">
        <p>
            When RStudio first starts up, you'll notice that it prints out the version 
            of R that it is currently running. 
        </p>
        <p>
            There are two other tabs here "Terminal" and "Jobs" which can be ignored for the beginner. 
        </p>
        <p>
            To use R in the most basic sense, you can begin typing on the row with the 
            small arrow (<code>></code>) and press enter. The output will be printed 
            directly below. 
        </p>
        <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto"
        src="../img//00-img/console-output.png">
    </section>
    <section id="nav--files">
        <h3>Files/Plots</h3>
        <p>
            This bottom right corner is where you can see any current plots, and the 
            files on your computer that are in your current working directory.
        </p>
        <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto"
        src="../img//00-img/files-plots.png">
        <p>
            You'll notice that there is no plot displayed right now, but should we 
            generate a plot and display it from a script, it would pop up here for us 
            to view. If we navigate to the "Files" tab, we would see the files that are 
            in the current directory that RStudio is working in. 
        </p>
    </section>
    <section id="nav--env">
        <h3>Environment</h3>
        <p>
            This top right panel is an important one. R will display all the objects 
            you create through the course of your programming here. That is, any 
            variables or functions you create, with the name and a brief description 
            will be here. To view these objects when they exist, you may click on them 
            directly from the environment panel. 
        </p>
        <img class="image-full-page" style="display:block;margin:auto"
        src="../img//00-img/env.png">
        <p>
            The beginner may ignore the other tabs in this panel. 
        </p>
    </section>
    <section id="most">
        <h2>Getting the most out of RStudio</h2>
        <p>
            RStudio is a really rich environment for programming. Once you're familiar 
            with the basics, it can really speed up your work to learn a few shortcuts 
            or tips and tricks. We recommend you become familiar with generally how the 
            software works, then once you're comfortable you can branch out. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Here is a link to some <a 
            href="https://www.dataquest.io/blog/rstudio-tips-tricks-shortcuts/">tips 
            & tricks to get you started</a>
        
        </p>
    </section>
</section>


